## The reef is worth it. The crowd isn't.

The Red Sea deserves its reputation. The water is clear in a way that doesn't quite photograph, the coral is alive and close to the surface, and the fish don't seem to mind you. What gets in the way is almost never the sea — it's the way most trips sell it: a hundred and twenty people on a party boat, one snorkel stop on a stopwatch, a queue for the ladder and a scramble for a spot in the water. You came to float over a reef, and you spend the day managing other people's schedules.

Take the boat privately and the whole thing inverts. It becomes your day on your water.

## A boat that bends to you

Private here means exactly that: your own vessel, your own skipper, and a day with no fixed itinerary but yours. You decide which reefs, how long you stay in the water, when you want lunch, whether you'd rather chase the best coral or find the calmest, emptiest bay and just drift. The skipper knows which spots are sheltered and quiet on the day's wind, and he takes you there — not to whichever mooring the big operators have block-booked.

There's no scrum for the ladder because there's no crowd. You get in the water where the fish actually are, and you get out when you're ready.

> The sea was never the problem. It was always the two hundred other people the ticket came with.

## Handled, so the day is just the water

Hotel or marina pickup, the boat readied and fuelled, gear aboard, lunch cooking, and your consigliere on the phone if you need anything at all. You bring a towel and a rough idea of the kind of day you're after — lively and reef-hopping, or slow and sun-drenched — and we build the rest around it.

It's the simplest luxury on the coast: the whole Red Sea, for a day, with nobody else's timetable laid over the top of it.
